Introduction of the topic and dataset¶

Introduction to PISA (ref.: NCES 2014-024, U.S. Department of Education)¶

What Is PISA?¶

The Program for International Student Assessment (PISA) is a system of international assessments that allows countries to compare outcomes of learning as students near the end of compulsory schooling. PISA core assessments measure the performance of 15-year-old students in mathematics, science, and reading literacy every 3 years. Coordinated by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), PISA was first implemented in 2000 in 32 countries. It has since grown to 65 education systems in 2012.

What PISA Measures¶

PISA’s goal is to assess students’ preparation for the challenges of life as young adults. PISA assesses the application of knowledge in mathematics, science, and reading literacy to problems within a reallife context (OECD 1999). PISA does not focus explicitly on curricular outcomes and uses the term “literacy” in each subject area to indicate its broad focus on the application of knowledge and skills. For example, when assessing mathematics, PISA examines how well 15-year-old students can understand, use, and reflect on mathematics for a variety of real-life problems and settings that they may not encounter in the classroom. Scores on the PISA scales represent skill levels along a continuum of literacy skills.

Each PISA data collection cycle assesses one of the three core subject areas in depth (considered the major subject area), although all three core subjects are assessed in each cycle (the other two subjects are considered minor subject areas for that assessment year). Assessing all three subjects every 3 years allows countries to have a consistent source of achievement data in each of the three subjects, while rotating one area as the primary focus over the years. Mathematics was the major subject area in 2012, as it was in 2003, since each subject is a major subject area once every three cycles. In 2012, mathematics, science, and reading literacy were assessed primarily through a paper-and-pencil assessment, and problem solving was administered via a computer-based assessment. In addition to these core assessments, education systems could participate in optional paper-based financial literacy and computer-based mathematics and reading assessments. The United States participated in these optional assessments. Visit www.nces.ed.gov/surveys/pisa for more information on the PISA assessments, including information on how the assessments were designed and examples of PISA questions.

Introduction to the PISA 2012 dataset¶

PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. It is not a conventional school test. Rather than examining how well students have learned the school curriculum, it looks at how well prepared they are for life beyond school.

Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science representing about 28 million 15-year-olds globally. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

Dataset Investigation and Preliminary Wrangling¶

The dataset consisted of 485490 observations with 636 variables. After looking into the raw data and data dictionary, we decided to focus on the effects of family-based factors (e.g., language at home, household possessions, family status, parents' working status, and parents' education levels) on the students' academic performance. We started the exploration by wrangling the data accordingly.

Assessing WEALTH, CULTPOS, HEDRES¶

Collecting information about household possessions as indicators of family wealth has received much attention in international studies in the field of education (Spiezia, 2010; Traynor and Raykov, 2013). Household assets are believed to capture wealth better than income because they reflect a more stable source of wealth. Three indices were derived from these items: i) family wealth possessions (WEALTH), ii) cultural possessions (CULTPOS), iii) home educational resources (HEDRES). We plotted the histograms of each index as well as the bivariate scatterplots between the each index and Math_score.

We can see from the hisotgrams that these indexs contain a large amount of negative values, which is not tally with their definition and coding rules. We couldn't find any information explaining the negative values of these indexs neither from the technical report nor internet. The scatterplots couldn't show any meaningful trends either. Therefore, we decided to drop these three variables.

In [38]:
# drop `WEALTH`, `CULTPOS`, AND `HEDRES`
pisa_home.drop(columns = ['WEALTH', 'CULTPOS', 'HEDRES'], inplace = True)

Since we need to find out whether a student comes from a single-parent family or two-parent family, we will perform feature engineering to create a variable - Family_status to tell us this information.

In [41]:
# create a new variable `Family_status`
pisa_home_clean['Family_status'] = pisa_home_clean['Live_with_mother'] + pisa_home_clean['Live_with_father']
In [42]:
# define the categories of the new created variable `Family_status`
pisa_home_clean.loc[pisa_home_clean['Family_status'] == "YesYes", 'Family_status'] = 'Live with both'
pisa_home_clean.loc[pisa_home_clean['Family_status'] == "YesNo", 'Family_status'] = 'Live with mother'
pisa_home_clean.loc[pisa_home_clean['Family_status'] == "NoYes", 'Family_status'] = 'Live with father'
pisa_home_clean.loc[pisa_home_clean['Family_status'] == "NoNo", 'Family_status'] = 'Live with none'

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 485490 observations in the dataset with 636 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The dataset consisted of with 636 variables. After looking into the raw data and data dictionary, we decided to focus on the effects of family-based factors(e.g., language at home, household possessions, family status, parents' working status, and parents' education levels) on the students' academic performance. We will also look into the difference among countrie.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that family status, parents' working status, and parents' education levels will have significant effect on the test scores. I also think that the other family-based factors will have effects on the scores, though to a much smaller degree. We are also interested to see the difference among countries.

Distribution of Family-based Categorical Variables¶

We would also like to see the distribution of the categorical variables we are interested in. Moreover, for each categorical variable, we would like to see the frequency of each category in a certain order. The best thing for us to do is to convert the categorical variables into ordered categorical data type. By doing this, the order of categories becomes innate to the feature, and we don't need to specify an "order" parameter each time we plot them.

In [48]:
# remove the trailing spaces for volumns 'Books_at_home', 'Mother_job', and 'Father_job'

pisa_home_clean['Mother_job'] = pisa_home_clean['Mother_job'].str.rstrip()
pisa_home_clean['Father_job'] = pisa_home_clean['Father_job'].str.rstrip()

# convert 'Family_status', 'Books_at_home', 'Edu_level_mother', 'Edu_level_father', 'Highest_edu_level_parents' 
# 'Mother_job', 'Father_job' into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'Family_status': ['Live with both', 'Live with mother', 'Live with father', 'Live with none'],
                    'Books_at_home': ['0-10 books', '11-25 books', '26-100 books', '101-200 books', '201-500 books', 
                                      'More than 500 books'],
                    'Edu_level_mother': ['None','ISCED 1','ISCED 2','ISCED 3B, C', 'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','ISCED 5A, 6'],
                    'Edu_level_father': ['None','ISCED 1','ISCED 2','ISCED 3B, C', 'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','ISCED 5A, 6'],
                    'Highest_edu_level_parents': ['None','ISCED 1','ISCED 2','ISCED 3B, C', 'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','ISCED 5A, 6'],
                    'Mother_job': ['Working full-time <for pay>', 'Working part-time <for pay>', 
                                   'Not working, but looking for a job', 'Other (e.g. home duties, retired)'],
                    'Father_job': ['Working full-time <for pay>', 'Working part-time <for pay>', 
                                   'Not working, but looking for a job', 'Other (e.g. home duties, retired)']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    pisa_home_clean[var] = pisa_home_clean[var].astype(ordered_var)

Country vs. Score¶

How do the scores distribute among countries? Which countries are the leaders in terms of academic performance?

In [101]:
# plot the distribution of all subject scores by country with descending order by score ranking

plt.figure(figsize = [15, 20])
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace = 0.98) # adjust spacing between subplots, in order to show long country names nicely

math_score_country_order = pisa_home_clean.groupby('Country')['Math_score'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False).index
reading_score_country_order = pisa_home_clean.groupby('Country')['Reading_score'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False).index
science_score_country_order = pisa_home_clean.groupby('Country')['Science_score'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False).index

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
sb.boxplot(data = pisa_home_clean, x = 'Math_score', y = 'Country', order = math_score_country_order, color = sb.color_palette()[9]);
plt.ylabel('Countries (ordered descendingly by score ranking)')
plt.title('Math score distributions by country');

plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
sb.boxplot(data = pisa_home_clean, x = 'Reading_score', y = 'Country', order = reading_score_country_order, color = sb.color_palette()[9]);
plt.ylabel(''); # Remove the redundant label
plt.title('Reading score distributions by country');

plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
sb.boxplot(data = pisa_home_clean, x = 'Science_score', y = 'Country', order = science_score_country_order, color = sb.color_palette()[9]);
plt.ylabel(''); # Remove the redundant label
plt.title('Science score distributions by country');

We plotted the score as boxchart for each country according to the decreasing order ranked by the average performance of countries. We noticed that:

  • Most countries ranking from 10th to 40th seem to perform comparably to each other.
  • The top players outperform significantly over the other countries for all three subjects, espcially the 1st player - China-Shanghai.
  • The box-and-wiskers plot allows us to see the outliers for each country. For example, we find that, the outstanding results of math come from China-Shanghai, while the outstanding results of reading come from Japan, and that of science from Singapore. Although it's not the focus of this study, the underlying reasons can be explored by checking the influencing factors of the difference among countries.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Language at home is supposed to influence the test score as students who speak the same language as test language is likely to perform better than students who speak a different language. Multivariate Exploration¶

The main thing I want to explore in this part of the analysis is how the effect of family status and parent employment status identified in bivariate exploration vary among countries.

Plot Matrices of Math_score, Reading_score, and Science_score¶

We are interested to see if scores of different subjects are correlated to each other, that is, can we infer that students who score high on one subject is most likely to score high on the other two subjects.

Therefore, we are going to study the pair-by-pair relationship between Math Scores, Reading Scores and Science Scores, and correlate them in pair scatter plots, in order to see the type and strength of potential correlation.

In [129]:

There is a strong positive correlation between each pair of the three variables. Therefore, for the following two multivariate analysis, we will only plot the visualizations using Math_score.

The Facetgrid plot shows that in most countries, students in homes with two parents do better in all three subjects. Exceptions can be observed for Montenegro, Peru, and Vietnam. In these countries, students live with mother only score higher than students who live with both parents. One possible reason may be that fathers in these countries failed to put enough effort in children's education.

As observed in bivariate exploration, students with neither parent living at home have the lowest achievement in most countries, except for Estonia, Hong Kong-China, Jordan, Japan, Singapore, Tunisia. Among these exceptions, Estonia, Hong Kong-China, Japan, and Singapore rank high in the test, while Jordan and Tunisia rank very low. The reasons can be explored in future study by taking into account other variables.

In this section, the positive correlationship between Math_score, Reading_score, and Science_score is identifed. I also extended my investigation of the influence of family-based factors on test scores by looking at the impact of country. The multivariate exploration here showed that the general influence of family-based factors is valid for most countries, with a few exceptions. Since we only focus of family-based factors in this study, there could be other factors such as school factors or society factors that make the divergence.
